{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491189","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491189"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:36:47+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:36:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"863"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"863","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/863"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.16,0.3,0.02,0.49,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"863"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92701"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"863","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/863"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"863"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76062"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"163"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"4992"},{"type":"contributions","id":"5362"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30224"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43040"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92701","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/92701"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 70-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with painless swelling of multiple finger joints that has gradually worsened over the past year. The swelling now interferes with her activities of daily living. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe has a 15-year history of recurrent episodes of acute joint pain and swelling which she has managed with short courses of ibuprofen. Her medical history includes hypertension and nephrolithiasis 10 years ago. She takes amlodipine but has avoided other regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Her fingers show multiple firm, white-yellow nodular deposits around the joints with associated deformity (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Rheumatoid arthritis","Osteoarthritis","Psoriatic arthritis","Tophaceous gout","Scleroderma"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with the classic appearance of \u003Cstrong\u003Etophaceous gout\u003C/strong\u003E, characterised by painless, firm, white-yellow nodular deposits (tophi) that represent accumulated urate crystals in and around joints. This chronic presentation contrasts markedly with acute gout flares, which are characterised by severe pain, erythema, and inflammation. The chronic history of untreated inflammatory arthritis, along with risk factors of hypertension and previous nephrolithiasis, supports this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERheumatoid arthritis\u003C/strong\u003E typically causes symmetrical joint deformities including swan neck deformity, boutonni\u00e8re deformity, and ulnar deviation, but does not cause the characteristic tophi seen here. The pattern of joint involvement typically affects metacarpophalangeal and proximal interphalangeal joints.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOsteoarthritis\u003C/strong\u003E predominantly affects distal interphalangeal joints with Heberden\u0027s nodes. The pain is typically mechanical rather than inflammatory, and bony rather than tophaceous deposits would be seen.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPsoriatic arthritis\u003C/strong\u003E can present with various patterns including distal interphalangeal involvement, but would typically have associated skin and nail changes. The deposits seen here are not characteristic of psoriatic arthritis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EScleroderma\u003C/strong\u003E causes skin tightening and fibrosis rather than nodular deposits. Associated features would include Raynaud\u0027s phenomenon, telangiectasia, and nail fold capillary changes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EManagement of tophaceous gout requires aggressive urate-lowering therapy with a target serum urate level below 0.30 mmol/L, which is lower than the usual target of 0.36 mmol/L for uncomplicated gout. This prevents further crystal deposition and may lead to gradual resolution of tophi.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Tophi are painless deposits of urate crystals that develop in chronic undertreated gout, in contrast to the severe pain of acute flares","Risk factors for gout include hypertension and history of nephrolithiasis","Chronic tophaceous gout requires more aggressive urate-lowering therapy with lower serum urate targets"],"references":["Talley NJ, O\u2019Connor S. The rheumatological system. In: Talley NJ, editor. Clinical examination: a systematic guide to physical diagnosis. 6th ed. Chatswood (NSW): Elsevier; 2014. p. 241-294","Denton CP, Khanna D. Systemic sclerosis. The Lancet. 2017 Oct 7;390(10103):1685\u201399.","Dalbeth N, Gosling AL, Gaffo A, Abhishek A. Gout. Lancet. 2021 May 15;397(10287):1843\u201355."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76062"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"863"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"14245"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"14245","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/14245"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/9c90ed4f-6102-4776-b65c-f4af5811008c.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/m